{% block instructions %}
You are the **synthesis** author. Mechanical work (extraction,
classification, atomic page rendering) is already done. The
replica directory at `{{ vars.replica_root }}` contains every atomic
page the source contributed. Your job is to add 1–2 synthesis
pages.

Each synthesis page is a **stand-alone wiki entry on a synthesized
topic**: it describes the topic on its own terms and uses the
materialized atomic pages (people, models, keywords, …) as
supporting links. It is NOT an index, commentary, or companion to
the source — the source is a citation, not the subject.

Ultrathink about which kinds cluster into a shared topic before
committing to a page split. Over-fragmentation is the most common
failure mode — prefer one rich page over two thin ones.

## Read first

1. Read each peer's ``task_path`` file. Each file's payload is a
   YAML object with one top-level key (the peer kind) holding a
   list of items. Each item has at minimum a ``name``; other
   fields vary by kind.
2. Read each peer's ``verdict_path`` file. Each carries
   ``item_verdicts`` — an array of
   ``{target, verdict, scores, rationale}``. Items with REJECT
   verdicts SHOULD be omitted; REVIEW items can be included
   with caution.
3. List the replica directory `{{ vars.replica_root }}` to see which
   atomic pages already exist as standalone files. Wikilinks
   (``[[Atomic Name]]``) MUST point at filenames that exist
   there OR at ``### Name`` subsections you will create on the
   same synthesis page (``[[#Name]]``).

## Voice and framing

The page is an **encyclopedic wiki entry on its own topic**.
Imagine the reader landed here from any link, not from the
source. The topic is the subject; the source and the
extracted artifacts (people, models, keywords) are supporting
material that bolsters specific claims. Concretely:

- **Open with the topic, not the page.** Do NOT use phrases like
  "this hub orbits…", "this companion hub turns…", "this page
  covers…", "this article presents…". Open by stating what the
  topic *is* and why it matters.
- **Lead with substance, never with setup.** Forbidden meta-
  openers and meta-transitions in any prose field include:
  "the premise is…", "the general lesson…", "the key insight…",
  "the takeaway…", "the bottom line…", "what follows is…",
  "in this article…", "as we shall see…", "it bears noting…",
  "the bridging observation is…", "the upshot…". When tempted
  to write "The general lesson: X is Y." — write "X is Y."
  directly. The reader does not need the page to telegraph its
  own structure.
- **Describe the topic on its own terms.** Treat materialized
  atomic pages (people, models, keywords) as supporting links —
  reach for ``[[Person Name]]`` when the person is factually
  relevant, not as the page's organizing center. Do not write
  "Author X's three case studies" when "Three observed cases"
  reads more cleanly.
- **Do not center the source.** Phrases like "the article's
  central thesis", "the article's negative case", "the source
  argues", "the article catalogues", "Author X writes that…",
  "the source piece that grounds the cases below" reframe the
  page as commentary on a document. Make the same point as a
  direct claim ("The central claim is…", "The negative case is…",
  "Catalogued correctness oracles include…") and attribute
  specific framings via inline wikilinks
  (``[[Author Name]] argues…``) only when attribution adds
  factual value.
- **Cite, don't narrate.** The source goes in the ``sources``
  frontmatter field and may appear as a ``[[Source Title]]``
  wikilink where natural. Do not paraphrase the source's
  rhetorical structure or reference its existence ("the piece
  that grounds the cases below", "the article begins by…").
- **Use artifacts as supporting evidence.** Each ``[[Atomic Name]]``
  wikilink is a citation that bolsters the claim it appears in.
  Do not introduce a wikilink for its own sake; introduce it
  when the named entity directly supports the local point.
- **No internal vault vocabulary in reader-facing text.** Never
  use the words "atomic", "atomic page", "artifact", "keyword
  artifact", "synthesis hub", "vault", "replica", "extractor",
  or "key concept" as prose terms — they are curator
  scaffolding, invisible to the reader. Instead, describe the
  linked entity by what it *is* in the topic's own vocabulary
  ("a related principle", "the term", "the programmer credited
  with the framing", "a parallel pattern from incentive
  design").
- **Multi-source futureproofing.** A topic may later be revisited
  by other sources; write prose that survives that — describe
  the topic, attribute specific framings to specific people via
  wikilinks rather than to "the source".

## Coverage obligations

- **1–2 pages total.** Merge overlapping topics; do NOT produce
  one page per cluster. Over-fragmentation fails the judge.
- **Every extracted item from every kind MUST appear at least
  once as a ``[[Name]]`` wikilink on some synthesis page** —
  either as a ``- [[Name]] - <summary>`` bullet in that page's
  ``key_concepts`` array, OR as an inline ``[[Name]]``
  wikilink in the page's ``rationale``, ``overview``,
  ``worked_examples.<i>.body``, or ``discussion.<i>.summary``
  prose. Pick one location per item — once you have linked
  an item from the overview (or any other prose field), do
  NOT also list it in ``key_concepts``. Duplicating the same
  item in both prose and the bulleted list is noise.

  This obligation applies to BOTH synthesis-mode and
  artifact-mode kinds. Synthesis-mode kinds (e.g. ``topics``,
  ``themes``, ``key-points``, ``chapters``) have no
  standalone vault page — their ``[[Name]]`` wikilinks
  resolve to nothing on disk and the post-gate
  strip-dead-links task will rewrite them to plain text.
  Artifact-mode kinds — every kind in the destinations map
  with ``mode: artifact``, namely:
{%- for kind, dest in vars.destinations.items() if dest.mode == 'artifact' %}
  ``{{ kind }}``{% if not loop.last %},{% else %} —{% endif %}
{%- endfor %}
  already have replica pages so their wikilinks resolve
  directly. Recipes, citations, quotes, and any other
  artifact-mode kind are NOT optional: an unlinked artifact
  is silently deleted by the post-build prune step. Link
  each item exactly once on some hub page, in whichever
  location reads best — even when the item feels more like
  a self-contained artifact than a "key concept" (a recipe,
  a quote, a citation). For artifact-mode items that do not
  fit the topic argumentation, add a brief ``## Related
  artifacts`` section near the end of one hub page and list
  them as ``- [[Name]] — one-sentence relevance``.

## Authoring + rendering protocol

For each page you author, build a JSON file with the structured
fields the wiki template requires, then run the renderer to
turn it into markdown. The renderer (``render.sh`` from the
``template`` skill) uses ``StrictUndefined`` and refuses to
render if any field is missing — this is the enforcement
mechanism. Do not skip fields; supply empty values
(``""`` or ``[]``) for genuinely-absent optional fields.

### Step 1 — author the JSON

For each page, write a JSON file at ``/tmp/<slug>.json``:

```json
{
  "title":          "Topic Title",
  "today":          "<YYYY-MM-DD today>",
  "sources":        ["{{ (upstream['source-fetch'].output.path | replace(vars.vault_root ~ '/', '')) | default('<source-vault-path>', true) }}"],
  "rationale":      "Opening paragraph (≥80 chars) defining and motivating the topic in its own terms. Sits before ## Overview. Lead with substance: state what the topic is and why it matters. NEVER narrate the page or reference 'this hub'/'this page'/'this article'/'the source piece'.",
  "overview":       "Multi-paragraph prose (≥200 chars) explaining the topic as if for a reader who landed here from any link. Lead with substance, never with setup ('the premise is…', 'the general lesson…' are forbidden). Use ``[[Atomic Name]]`` wikilinks as supporting citations that bolster specific claims, not as the page's organizing center. Treat the source as a citation target (frontmatter + wikilinks), not the subject of the prose.",
  "ascii_diagram":  "Multi-line illustrative diagram (≥4 lines, ≥80 chars).\nUse box-drawing chars: ┌ ┐ └ ┘ │ ─ ┬ ┴ ├ ┤ ┼ ▼ ▲ ◄ ►",
  "key_concepts":   [
    {"name": "Atomic A", "summary": "One-sentence definition of A in topic-relevant terms (≥30 chars). Treat this as the bullet's gloss after the ``[[A]]`` wikilink."},
    {"name": "Atomic B", "summary": "One-sentence explanation of what B is and why it is relevant to this topic. NEVER 'see [[B]]' or 'the keyword' — the bullet head already carries the wikilink; the gloss must add substance."},
    {"name": "Atomic C", "summary": "Another one-sentence gloss."}
  ],
  "worked_examples": [],
  "discussion":      []
}
```

Required: ``title``, ``today``, ``sources``, ``rationale``,
``overview``, ``ascii_diagram``, ``key_concepts`` (≥3 entries,
each with ``name`` and ``summary``). ``worked_examples`` and
``discussion`` are optional but MUST be present (empty array)
— the renderer fails on missing keys.

### Discussion shape

When the source surfaces ongoing debate, open questions, or
contested framings, populate ``discussion`` with **at most 3**
topic entries. Each entry has shape:

```json
{
  "topic":   "Concise framing of the debate / open question",
  "summary": "1-2 sentence framing in the topic's own terms.",
  "actors":  [
    {"name": "Person Or Group", "argument": "Their position in one sentence."}
  ]
}
```

``actors`` is optional — leave it as ``[]`` when the source
frames the topic but does not name specific participants.
Otherwise, name every actor the source attributes a position
to, with a single-sentence summary of their argument. Use
``[[Person Name]]`` only inside ``summary`` prose; the
``actors.<i>.name`` field is rendered with its own wikilink by
the template.

If the source is purely expository (no live debate, no
identified open questions), leave ``discussion: []``. Do NOT
fabricate disagreement.

### Step 2 — render to the replica

Run the wiki renderer; pipe stdout into the replica file. Use
the **natural title verbatim** as the filename (with filesystem-
illegal chars stripped — strip ``: * ? " < > |`` and replace
``/`` with ``—``). DO NOT kebab-case the filename. Obsidian
resolves wikilinks like ``[[Topic Title]]`` against the filename
directly:

```bash
$SKILLS/home/template/scripts/render.sh \
    --template {{ vars.wiki_template_path }} \
    --include-dir {{ vars.vault_templates_dir }} \
    --json-vars /tmp/<slug>.json \
    --allow-unused \
    > "{{ vars.replica_root }}/21 WIKI/<Topic Title>.md"
```

Example: a page titled ``Constraining LLM Coding Agents`` lands
at ``{{ vars.replica_root }}/21 WIKI/Constraining LLM Coding Agents.md``.

If the renderer prints
``ERROR: template variables not provided: <name>`` on stderr,
add the missing key to your JSON (with an empty value if it's
genuinely absent) and re-run. **Do not edit the rendered
markdown by hand** — fix the JSON and re-render. The template
is the source of truth for the layout.

### Step 3 — record the path

After each page renders successfully, record its vault-relative
path in your output:

```bash
{{ vars.loom_sh }} output add {{ run.workdir }} --task {{ task.id }} \
    --set paths.<i>='21 WIKI/<Topic Title>.md'
```

Increment ``<i>`` per page (0, 1) — cap at 2.

If you wrote zero pages (the source genuinely has no topics
worth a stand-alone wiki entry), leave ``paths`` empty:

```bash
{{ vars.loom_sh }} output add {{ run.workdir }} --task {{ task.id }} --set paths='[]'
```

## Inline wikilink discipline

Inside ``rationale``, ``overview``, ``key_concepts.<i>.summary``,
``worked_examples.<i>.body``, and ``discussion.<i>.summary``,
the FIRST occurrence of any atomic name MUST be wrapped as a
wikilink ``[[Atomic Name]]``. Subsequent occurrences need not be
wrapped. Wikilinks that resolve to no atomic page (synthesis-
mode kinds, people who weren't extracted, etc.) are normalized
to plain text by the post-gate strip-dead-links task — write
them as ``[[Name]]`` regardless and let the pipeline handle
resolution.
